# Goal

Create the initial `viewer.html` file that sets up a basic Three.js scene with a camera, a renderer, and the ability to render a 3D environment. This file will serve as the foundation for visualizing the robot and its motions.

# Tools and preparation

- The folder structure from the previous task (`robot_viewer/`)
- A text editor (e.g., VS Code, Sublime Text, or Notepad++)
- A web browser (e.g., Chrome or Firefox)

# Steps

## 1. Open your `robot_viewer/` folder in your text editor

- Launch your text editor.
- Use ‚ÄúOpen Folder‚Äù or ‚ÄúFile > Open‚Äù to select the `robot_viewer/` folder you created in the last task.

## 2. Open or create `viewer_template.html`

- If `viewer_template.html` already exists, open it.
- If not, create a new file and name it exactly `viewer_template.html` (not `.txt`).

## 3. Add basic HTML structure

Copy and paste the following code into the file:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <title>1-DOF Robot Viewer</title>
  <style>
    body { margin: 0; overflow: hidden; }
    canvas { display: block; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <script type="module">
    import * as THREE from './three/three.min.js';

    const scene = new THREE.Scene();
    scene.background = new THREE.Color(0xeeeeee);

    const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(
      75, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000
    );
    camera.position.set(0, 0, 100);

    const renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer({ antialias: true });
    renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
    document.body.appendChild(renderer.domElement);

    function animate() {
      requestAnimationFrame(animate);
      renderer.render(scene, camera);
    }
    animate();

    window.addEventListener('resize', () => {
      camera.aspect = window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight;
      camera.updateProjectionMatrix();
      renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
4. Save the file
Use File > Save, or press Ctrl + S / Cmd + S.

5. Open the file in a browser
Navigate to the robot_viewer/ folder in your file explorer.

Double-click viewer_template.html to open it in your default browser.

You should see a blank gray screen (this means the renderer is working correctly).

6. Troubleshooting (if screen is blank or console shows errors)
Right-click and choose "Inspect" or press F12 to open the browser console.

Check for file path errors (e.g., three.min.js not found).

Make sure all script paths match your actual folder structure and filenames.

7. Celebrate
üéâ You've built a functioning 3D scene scaffold! You're now ready to add OrbitControls, load robot models, and animate joints in the next steps.

